今天早上，Registers的Tim Anderson发布了CentOS项目的Brian Exelbierd的访谈摘录。 Exelbierd是CentOS董事会的成员，并且是与Red Hat的官方联络人。 Exelbierd与安德森（Anderson）进行了交谈，以提供内部人士对Red Hat在12月有效终止CentOS Linux的看法，其中开源巨头宣布将立即弃用CentOS Linux，并将安全升级到CentOS Linux 8将于2021年晚些时候终止，而不是CentOS用户预期的2029年支持终止日期。
  ＆＃34; CentOS是[Red Hat]赞助的项目，＆＃34; Exelbierd告诉名册。 ＆＃34;我们是资助机构（接受和支付赠款的实体），并且我们也恰好是一个重要的捐助者。我们了解到开源社区在独立性方面做得很好。我们让那些理事机构来治理。＆＃34;
 当然，在这些特定细节中，魔鬼是CentOS董事会无法决定Red Hat工程团队的工作。这就是Exelbierd前面提到的贡献，特别是Red Hat工程团队的工作。根据Exelbierd的说法，Red Hat决定我们将对我们指导投资的方式进行一些根本性的改变，然后进入CentOS项目并说，这是Red Hat要做的事情。＆＃34;
 那件事是在优先考虑对CentOS Stream的投资时，停止了对Red Hat对CentOS Linux的支持，Exelbierd将其描述为“关键”。红帽。 ＆＃34;我们整理了案子，并说我们正在转移我们的工程贡献，在某些情况下需要人们的时间...我们希望引起您的注意，因为取决于您决定做什么可能导致的潜在责任问题，因此我们要确保您有一个计划。＆＃34;
     Exelbierd说，短期利润（一些最终用户从免费使用CentOS Linux到付费RHEL订阅的迁移）不是公司的主要动力。他指出，为那些打算改用RHEL的人员提供的电子邮件地址不会发送给销售部门，而是发送给我和该业务部门的两位同事的电子邮件地址。他说。
 Exelbierd并不是在寻找小额销售，而是在寻找反馈-Red Hat传统上从未从CentOS用户那里收到反馈，大多数CentOS用户从未打电话，从未写信，他们不与我们互动。 。＆＃34;他说，反馈地址是业务模型。绝对不是给销售人员的邮件列表，没人想去追随拥有一台服务器，两台服务器，16台服务器的人。肯定会有某些人为其CentOS Linux ...绝对会成为他们的付费RHEL。但是我们的目标不是坐下来让每个CentOS Linux用户成为RHEL的收入客户。＆＃34;
 关于CentOS Stream中代码的质量和就绪性，Exelbierd说，已经替换了CentOS的向前跟踪滚动版本。它正在进行中。＆＃34;如果我们的客户可以快速吸收变更，那就是我们要运送的变更。 [许多] CentOS Linux用户每天晚上都要运行yum更新...流将为[他们]做同样的事情。 [他们]已经在很多方面引领着Stream的生活。＆＃34; 
RHEL现在明确免费提供16台服务器。这可能应该在文章的某处。
  是的，直到不再正确，IBM再次更改规则。
    这直接来自他们的IBM霸主。 IBM将从RedHat及其用户中挤出每一分钱的收入，以弥补IBM在云世界中的劣势。
  我对这个错误信息感到厌烦。这是完全不对的，并且在这一点上使主张与阴谋论接壤。 IBM在Red Hat的日常运营中没有发言权。您知道我们需要RHEL的帮助吗？我们有一个合作伙伴帐户，并且像其他任何人一样提出了支持请求。拥有任何官方信息的每个人都会不断告诉您，但您没有在听。红帽曾表示这是CentOS /红帽团队而不是IBM的决定。 Arvind Krishna和Jim Whitehurst发布了博客和视频来澄清这一点（不过，我相信这些仅是内部的）。我们有一个闲暇的AMA频道，Jim专门讲了出来，以消除错误信息。我们发现它是在Red Hat之外的所有人都在同一时间被杀死的-正式公告发布时（我每天都与Red Hat密切合作）。对于那些不屑一顾的读者：IBM并没有杀死CentOS！在茶壶的这场暴风雨中，唯一真正可怕的事情是RedHat有一天宣布他们将进行此更改的方式，而且不管别人怎么想，这已经完成了。要么接受，要么离开它。他们牺牲了很多善意，超过了任何二年级的通讯专业学生都会以这种方式被否决。而且，尽管很多人都在说，IBM与决策无关。
  这个。这么多。正式而言，我认为我不允许对业务决策发表评论，但这不是我们的事情，因此我将说它不适用。 Red Hat确实为此丢下了球。周围的沟通不畅，很大程度上是造成不信任和不良意愿的原因。正如我所说，直到IBM内部与Red Hat支持和工程团队密切合作的人才知道这一消息，直到发布了公告。我不认为支持和工程团队[i]本身[/ i]知道。

note_en:
This morning, The Register&#39;s Tim Anderson published excerpts of an  interview with the CentOS project&#39;s Brian Exelbierd. Exelbierd is a member of the CentOS board and its official liaison with Red Hat. Exelbierd spoke to Anderson to give an insider&#39;s perspective on Red Hat&#39;s effective  termination of CentOS Linux in December, in which the open source giant announced CentOS Linux was to be deprecated immediately—with security upgrades to CentOS Linux 8 ending later in 2021 rather than the 2029 end of support date CentOS users expected.
  &#34;CentOS is a [Red Hat] sponsored project,&#34; Exelbierd told the Register. &#34;We are the funding agent (the entity which receives and disburses grants), and we also happen to be a heavy contributor. We have learned that open source communities do well with independence. We let those governing bodies govern.&#34;
 The devil in these particular details, of course, is that &#34;the CentOS board doesn&#39;t get to decide what Red Hat engineering teams do.&#34; This is the contribution that Exelbierd mentioned earlier—specifically, the labor of Red Hat engineering teams. According to Exelbierd, Red Hat decided &#34;we&#39;re going to make some fundamental changes in how we direct our investment,&#34; then &#34;went to the CentOS project and said, here is a thing Red Hat is going to do.&#34;
 That thing was the cessation of Red Hat&#39;s support for CentOS Linux while prioritizing its investment in CentOS Stream, which Exelbierd describes as &#34;critical&#34; to Red Hat. &#34;We laid out our case and we said that we&#39;re moving our engineering contribution, people time in some cases... we want to call your attention to them because depending on what you decide to do, there are potential liability issues that could result, so we want to make sure you have a plan.&#34;
     Exelbierd says that short-term profits—the migration of some end users from free use of CentOS Linux to paid RHEL subscriptions—was not a key motivator for the company. He pointed out that the email address offered for those considering a switch to RHEL doesn&#39;t go to the sales department—&#34;it goes to me and two of my colleagues in the business unit,&#34; he said.
 Rather than a bunch of small sales, Exelbierd says looking for feedback—the sort of feedback Red Hat has not traditionally received from CentOS users, most of whom &#34;never called, never write, they don&#39;t interact with us.&#34; The feedback address, he says, &#34;is the business model. It is absolutely not a mailing list for salespeople [...] nobody wants to go after the person with one server, two servers, 16 servers. There are definitely going to be some folks for whom their CentOS Linux... will become paid RHEL, absolutely. But our goal was not to sit down and make every CentOS Linux user a revenue RHEL customer.&#34;
 Regarding the quality and readiness of code in CentOS Stream, the forward-tracking rolling release CentOS has been replaced with, Exelbierd says &#34;this stuff has been tested. It is not work in progress.&#34; If our customers could consume change that fast, it&#39;s what we would ship. [A] lot of CentOS Linux users [run]  yum update every single night... Stream&#39;s going to do the same thing for [them]. [They&#39;re] already leading the Stream life, in a lot of ways.&#34;
  RHEL is now explicitly free for 16 servers. This should probably be somewhere in the article.
  Yeah, until it&#39;s no longer true and IBM changes the rules again.
    This is coming straight from their IBM overlords. IBM is going to squeeze every penny of revenue out of RedHat and its users to cover IBMs relegation to back of the bus in the cloud world.
  I&#39;m getting pretty sick of this misinformation. This is simply not true, and at this point parroting the claim borders on conspiracy theory.  IBM has no say in the day to day operations of Red Hat. You know what we do if we need help with RHEL? We have a partner account and put in a support request like anyone else.  Everyone with any official information keeps telling you this, but you&#39;re not listening. Red Hat have said that it was a decision by the CentOS/Red Hat teams, not IBM. Arvind Krishna and Jim Whitehurst have released blogs and videos clarifying this (I believe these are internal-only, however). We have an AMA channel on slack, and Jim spoke out specifically, to combat the misinformation. We found out it was being killed at the exact same moment everyone else outside of Red Hat did - when the official announcement came out (and I work closely with Red Hat on a daily basis).   And for those that didn&#39;t bother reading: IBM did not kill CentOS!    The only really awful thing in this tempest in a teapot, is the way RedHat just announced one day they were going to make this change and it doesn&#39;t matter what anyone thinks about it, it&#39;s a done deal. Take it or leave it. They sacrificed a lot of good will over what any second year communications student would have vetoed in the way it was revealed. And no, IBM had nothing to do with decision, despite what a lot of people are saying.
  This. So much this. Officially I don&#39;t think I&#39;m allowed to comment on business decisions, but this wasn&#39;t ours so I&#39;m gonna say it doesn&#39;t apply. Red Hat really dropped the ball on this. The poor communication around it is largely the cause of the mistrust and bad will. As I said, even those of us within IBM who work closely with Red Hat support and engineering teams didn&#39;t know until the announcement was posted. I don&#39;t think the support and engineering teams [i]themselves[/&#39;i] knew.
